[1]
Date: Thu 6 Mar 2003
From: Craig Stephen <CCH@MALA.BC.CA>

A Comment on Prevalence of Rabies in Bats in British Columbia
---------------------------------------------------
It is important to clarify the comments made by the moderator
regarding the proportion of bats in British Columbia that carry
rabies. To my knowledge, there has been no systematic survey of bat
populations for rabies prevalence in the province. The figure of 2-10
percent quoted represents the proportion of bats that are submitted
for rabies testing that in fact test positive. Bats typically are
tested in British Columbia only when there are concerns about
possible human exposure and/or the animal is demonstrating clinically
compatible behaviors. Therefore, this subpopulation is not
representative of the general bat population, and one can safely
assume over-estimates the overall population prevalence of rabies.
I feel a correction is required, as I would hate to see confusion
reinforced in the local public health community regarding the nature
of rabies risk in British Columbia. While prevalence estimates should
not affect the decision for post-exposure prophylaxis in any
individual case, it may affect recommendation on bat control. Given
this recent case, there will be a variety of proclamations about bats
as they emerge from their hibernation this summer. If folks modify
their risk estimates based on an erroneous prevalence estimate, it
could cause unnecessary clashes between public health and
conservation objectives in the province.
--
Craig Stephen DVM PhD
Centre for Coastal Health and
UBC Centre for Disease Control
Nanaimo, British Columbia
Canada
<CCH@MALA.BC.CA>
