[2]
Date: Fri 7 Mar 2003
From: Arthur King <kinga@inspection.gc.ca>

Updated Statistic for Insectivorous Bat-associated Rabies in North America
---------------------------------------------------
The moderator commented in part; "In the United States 24 (74
percent) of the 32 human rabies cases reported since 1990 have been
attributed to insectivorous bat-associated variants of rabies virus."
I am employed in regulatory veterinary medicine. My responsibilities
include rabies control. Since bat rabies is endemic in my district, I
try to keep abreast of current information. The statistics referred
to above actually relate to the period between 1990 and 2000. To date
since 2000, there have been an additional 4 cases of human rabies due
to bat strains in North America. The most recent case in British
Columbia is under investigation. The other 3 cases (Calif Mar/02,
Iowa Sep/02 and Tenn. Sep/02) had no history of a bat bite, although
there was documented contact in the Tennessee case.
In light of this, the correct statistic would be 36 cases of rabies
in humans in USA and Canada since 1990, 81 percent of which have been
attributed to insectivorous bat-associated variants of rabies virus,
with a history of bat bite being established in only 2 cases.
--
Arthur B. King DVM
District Veterinarian
Fort Erie, Ontario L2A 6M4
<kinga@inspection.gc.ca>
[I am indebted to Craig Stephen and Arthur King for these corrections
and updates. Regarding the prevalence of rabies in bats in British
Columbia, my comment as Moderator was extracted from the ProMED-mail
archive for 1998: see Rabies, bats - Canada (Victoria, British
Columbia) 19980731.1459. Dr. Stephen has further indicated that an
official government statement on the rates of positive bats being
tested can be obtained from the Canadian Food Inspection Agency
Lethbridge Laboratory (Animal Disease Research Institute), as they
are responsible for testing bats from western Canada. - Mod.CP]
